## Draw a line graph

msg.data:
MatPlotLib Basics

This library will help us to present all the findings we make while exploring the data

Draw a line graph

paragraphs.text:
%python
from scipy.stats import norm
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
# generate values from -3 to 3 with 0.001 between each
x = np.arange(-3, 3, 0.001)

plt.plot(x, norm.pdf(x))
plt.show()

%md
## Multiple Plot on One Graph

%python
plt.plot(x, norm.pdf(x))
# Now change a little bit the graph
# With the same values, change the mean around 1.0 and the standard deviation at 0.5
plt.plot(x, norm.pdf(x, 1.0, 0.5))
plt.show()

%md
## We can save the plot directly to a file too

msg.data: We can save the plot directly to a file too

paragraphs.text:
%python
# We need to re introduce the plotting in order to let something be written into the file
plt.plot(x, norm.pdf(x))
plt.plot(x, norm.pdf(x, 1.0, 0.5))
plt.savefig('/playground/myplot.png', format='png')

%md
## Also we can adjust the axes

msg.data: Also we can adjust the axes

paragraphs.text:
%python

axes = plt.axes()
# Set the X and Y axis min and max values
axes.set_xlim([-5, 5])
axes.set_ylim([0.0, 1.0])
# Set the steps for both axes, i.e. the tickts for every value
axes.set_xticks(list(range(-5, 6)))
axes.set_yticks(list(np.arange(0.0, 1.0, 0.1)))
plt.plot(x, norm.pdf(x))
plt.plot(x, norm.pdf(x, 1.0, 0.5))
plt.show()

%md
## Add a Grid

%python

axes = plt.axes()
# Set the X and Y axis min and max values
axes.set_xlim([-5, 5])
axes.set_ylim([0.0, 1.0])
# Set the steps for both axes, i.e. the tickts for every value
axes.set_xticks(list(range(-5, 6)))
axes.set_yticks(list(np.arange(0.0, 1.0, 0.1)))
axes.grid()
plt.plot(x, norm.pdf(x))
plt.plot(x, norm.pdf(x, 1.0, 0.5))
plt.show()

%md
## Change line types and colors

%python

axes = plt.axes()
# Set the X and Y axis min and max values
axes.set_xlim([-5, 5])
axes.set_ylim([0.0, 1.0])
# Set the steps for both axes, i.e. the tickts for every value
axes.set_xticks(list(range(-5, 6)))
axes.set_yticks(list(np.arange(0.0, 1.0, 0.1)))
axes.grid()
# b means blue and the dash means a solid line
plt.plot(x, norm.pdf(x), 'b-')
# g means green and the : means a dot line
plt.plot(x, norm.pdf(x, 1.0, 0.5), 'g:')
plt.show()

%md
## Labeling Axes and Adding a Legend

msg.data: Labeling Axes and Adding a Legend

paragraphs.text:
%python

axes = plt.axes()
# Set the X and Y axis min and max values
axes.set_xlim([-5, 5])
axes.set_ylim([0.0, 1.0])
# Set the steps for both axes, i.e. the tickts for every value
axes.set_xticks(list(range(-5, 6)))
axes.set_yticks(list(np.arange(0.0, 1.0, 0.1)))
axes.grid()
plt.xlabel('Greebles')
plt.ylabel('Probability')
# b means blue and the dash means a solid line
plt.plot(x, norm.pdf(x), 'b-')
# g means green and the : means a dot line
plt.plot(x, norm.pdf(x, 1.0, 0.5), 'g:')
# the first argument is the array of the plot names and the loc means the location in the graph
plt.legend(['Sneetches', 'Gacks'], loc=4)
plt.show()

## Now use in XKCD Style :)

%python

plt.xkcd()
fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)
ax.spines['right'].set_color('none')
ax.spines['top'].set_color('none')
plt.xticks([])
plt.yticks([])
ax.set_ylim([-30, 10])

data = np.ones(100)
data[70:] -= np.arange(30)

plt.annotate('THE DAY I REALIZED\nI COULD COOK BACON\nWHENEVER I WANTED',
            xy=(70, 1),arrowprops=dict(arrowstyle='->'), xytext=(15, -10))
            
plt.plot(data)
plt.xlabel('time')
plt.ylabel('my overall health')

%md
## Pie Chart

%python
#Remove the xkcd mode
plt.rcdefaults()

values = [12, 55, 4, 32, 14]
colors = ['r', 'g', 'b', 'c', 'm']
explode = [0, 0, 0.2, 0, 0]
labels = ['India', 'United States', 'Russia', 'China', 'Europe']
plt.pie(values, colors=colors, labels=labels, explode=explode)
plt.title('Student locations')
plt.show()

%md
## And a Bar Chart

%python
values = [12, 55, 4, 32, 14]
colors = ['r', 'g', 'b', 'c', 'm']
plt.bar(range(0, 5), values, color=colors)
plt.show()

%md
## Box & Whisker Plot
Useful for visualizing the spread & skew of data.
The red line represent the median og the data, and the box represents the bounds og the 1st and 3rd quartiles.
So, half of the data exists within the box.
The dotted-line "whiskers" indicate the range of the data - except for outliers, which are plotted outside the whiskers. Outliers are 1.5x or more the interquartile range.

This example below creates uniformly distributed random numbers between -40 and 60, plust a few outliers above 100 and below -100

msg.data:
Box & Whisker Plot

Useful for visualizing the spread & skew of data.
The red line represent the median og the data, and the box represents the bounds og the 1st and 3rd quartiles.
So, half of the data exists within the box.
The dotted-line “whiskers” indicate the range of the data - except for outliers, which are plotted outside the whiskers. Outliers are 1.5x or more the interquartile range.

This example below creates uniformly distributed random numbers between -40 and 60, plust a few outliers above 100 and below -100

paragraphs.text:
%python
uniformSkewed = np.random.rand(100) * 100 - 40
high_outliers = np.random.rand(10) * 50 + 100
low_outliers = np.random.rand(10) * -50 -100
data = np.concatenate((uniformSkewed, high_outliers, low_outliers))
plt.boxplot(data)
plt.show()
